=========================================================
OBJECT SLICING - WHY IS IT A PROBLEM? ⭐⭐⭐⭐⭐
=========================================================

Definition
----------

Object Slicing occurs when a Derived object is copied
into a Base object by value.

Only the Base part is copied.

The Derived-specific members and behavior are lost.
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Shape
{
public:
    virtual void draw()
    {
        cout << "Drawing Shape" << endl;
    }

    virtual ~Shape() = default;
};

class Circle : public Shape
{
public:
    void draw() override
    {
        cout << "Drawing Circle" << endl;
    }
};

// Passed by VALUE -> Object Slicing
void process(Shape s)
{
    s.draw();
}

int main()
{
    Circle c;

    process(c);

    return 0;
}
"Here, process() takes a Shape by value. When I pass a Circle object, 
the compiler creates a new Shape object by copying only the base-class part of Circle. The derived Circle portion is discarded—this is object slicing. 
Since s is now an actual Shape object,
s.draw() calls Shape::draw() instead of Circle::draw(). To avoid object slicing, I would pass Shape by reference or pointer."


Why does this work?

With a reference:

void process(Shape& s)

No copy is created. The reference s refers to the original Circle object.

Circle object
      ▲
      │
Shape& s

Since the actual object is still a Circle, the virtual function mechanism dispatches the call to:

Circle::draw();


Object slicing occurs when a derived object is copied into a base object by value.
Only the base portion is copied, and the derived-specific state is discarded. 

As a result, the copied object becomes a pure base object, 
and virtual function calls resolve to the base implementation. 
To avoid object slicing, always pass or store polymorphic objects using base class references or pointers.

